<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ911206-0051</DOCNO><DOCID>911206-0051.</DOCID><HL>   James Guerin Pleads Guilty   In International Arms Scam</HL><DATE>12/06/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A16</SO><CO>   TAXES</CO><MS>TECHNOLOGY (TEC)</MS><IN>AEROSPACE (ARO)INTERNATIONAL TRADE NEWS (TRD)</IN><NS>TAXES (TAX)TRADE ISSUES (TRD)</NS><GV>JUSTICE DEPARTMENT (JUS)</GV><RE>AFRICA (AF)ARABIAN PENINSULA (ARA)CHILE (CI)FAR EAST (FE)IRAQ (IZ)MIDDLE EAST (ML)NORTH AMERICA (NME)PAKISTAN (PK)SOUTH AFRICA (SF)SOUTH AMERICA (SM)UNITED ARAB EMIRATES (TC)UNITED STATES (US)</RE><LP>   WASHINGTON -- Former international arms-dealar JamesGuerin pleaded guilty to fraud, tax evasion and other chargesstemming from a $1 billion scheme that defrauded investors onboth sides of the Atlantic Ocean and smuggled high-techweaponry to South Africa.   Mr. Guerin, as expected, appeared before a federaldistrict court judge in Philadelphia to admit that hemasterminded what federal investigators have described as oneof the largest and most complex international white-collarcrimes in memory. The former Lancaster, Pa., businessman andphilanthropist built a backyard company into amultibillion-dollar defense electronics conglomerate, whicheventually merged with Ferranti PLC.</LP><TEXT>   As part of his guilty plea yesterday, Mr. Guerinacknowledged inflating the value of his company,International Signal andamp; Control Group PLC, by booking a totalof more than $1 billion in phony weapons contracts withPakistan, the United Arab Emirates and other customers beforeand after the merger.   Papers filed by prosecutors along with the plea show thatbetween 1982 and 1989, Mr. Guerin &quot;diverted for his personalbenefit&quot; more than $18 million, and that millions ofadditional dollars went to co-conspirators, South Africanstraveling in the U.S., and other expenses related to &quot;illegalexport activity.&quot;   Through his attorney, Mr. Guerin denied diverting morethan $18 million for himself and also denied that the mergerwas the main reason Ferranti wrote off nearly half its networth. Prosecutors said that Mr. Guerin faces a maximum oflife in prison and a $3 million fine. The grand jury probe iscontinuing, with prosecutors investigating Mr. Guerin'sdealings in Chile, Pakistan, Iraq and other Middle Easterncountries.</TEXT></DOC>